title: Big Ten power rankings: Buckeyes, Hawkeyes stay No. 1
text:
Big Ten power rankings: Buckeyes, Hawkeyes stay No. 1 Mike Carmin , mcarmin@jconline.com 7:53 a.m. EDT October 20, 2015 Ohio State Buckeyes wide receiver Braxton Miller (1) celebrates with head coach Urban Meyer after he scored against the Penn State Nittany Lions at Ohio Stadium. (Photo: Greg Bartram-USA TODAY Sports) 
It's not necessarily happy days for the state's Big Ten teams. Indiana lost in devastating fashion, surrendering a 25-point second half lead at home to Rutgers , while Purdue continues to struggle to find its conference footing and has now lost five in a row . 
Here are this week's Big Ten power rankings from Journal & Courier Purdue Insider Mike Carmin: EAST 
1. Ohio State (7-0, 3-0) 
Maybe it was the black uniforms that made J.T. Barrett the convincing choice as the team's top quarterback. More likely it was his four touchdowns. Saturday: at Rutgers 
2. Michigan State (7-0, 3-0) 
The Spartans needed a miracle to beat the Wolverines. It happened. Saturday: vs. Indiana 
3. Michigan (5-2, 2-1) 
It will take two weeks to get over losing to Michigan State in that fashion. Saturday: Bye 
4. Penn State (5-2, 2-1) 
Reaching eight wins is possible before closing with Michigan and Michigan State. Saturday: at Maryland Will IU football get another chance to handle success? 
5. Rutgers (3-3, 1-2) 
Coach Kyle Flood returns from a three-game suspension and watched the Scarlet Knights stun Indiana after trailing by 25 points late in the third quarter. Saturday: vs. Ohio State 
6. Indiana (4-3, 0-3) 
Epic collapse. Forget about the next three games - Michigan State, Iowa and Michigan. The season comes down to winning at Maryland and Purdue. Saturday: at Michigan State 
7. Maryland (2-4, 0-2) 
Not sure the bye week will cure the Terrapins. Saturday: vs. Penn State WEST 
Hawkeyes running back Akrum Wadley (25) runs the ball during the second half of the game against the Northwestern Wildcats at Ryan Field. (Photo: Caylor Arnold-USA TODAY Sports) 
1. Iowa (7-0, 3-0) 
The beat goes on for the Hawkeyes, who lost running back Jordan Canzeri to a leg injury at Northwestern. Akrum Wadley steps in and rushes for 204 yards and four touchdowns. Saturday: Bye 
2. Wisconsin (5-2, 2-1) 
More passing attempts than rushing attempts is working, for now. Saturday: at Illinois 
3. Northwestern (5-2, 1-2) 
Nice run while it lasted. The Wildcats have allowed 78 points the last two games. Saturday: at Nebraska 
â€‹ 4. Illinois (4-2, 1-1) 
The Illini likely won't end up this high, but no one else has earned this spot yet. Saturday: vs. Wisconsin Despite 1-6 mark, Boilers focused on staying together 
5. Nebraska (3-4, 1-2) 
The schedule sets up nicely for the Huskers to hit November with a 5-4 record. Saturday: vs. Northwestern 
6. Minnesota (4-3, 1-2) 
Who are the real Gophers? The team that walloped Purdue or the one that's been outscored 75-28 by Northwestern and Nebraska? Saturday: Bye 
7. Purdue (1-6, 0-3)
